T1  - Using the Lens Model to Magnify Raters' Consistency, Matching, and Shared Bias
AU  - Schmitt, Neal
AU  - Noe, Raymond A.
AU  - Gottschalk, Rand
Y1  - 1986/03/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255864
DO  - 10.5465/255864
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 130
EP  - 139
VL  - 29
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the authors discuss research they conducted that used the lens model to interpret how different groups on employees supplied performance ratings. The groups examined were supervisors, peers and subordinates. The methodology used by the authors allowed them to analyze the degree to which raters adopted a similar strategy in combining information and the degree to which their agreement was a function of job-relevant considerations or a function of shared biases. They note that their results provide useful information for increasing the effectiveness of performance rating systems.
AB  - In this article the authors discuss research they conducted that used the lens model to interpret how different groups on employees supplied performance ratings. The groups examined were supervisors, peers and subordinates. The methodology used by the authors allowed them to analyze the degree to which raters adopted a similar strategy in combining information and the degree to which their agreement was a function of job-relevant considerations or a function of shared biases. They note that their results provide useful information for increasing the effectiveness of performance rating systems.
