TY  - JOUR
T1  - Effects of Gender on Self- and Supervisory Ratings
AU  - Shore, Lynn McFarlane
AU  - Thornton, George C.
Y1  - 1986/03/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255863
DO  - 10.5465/255863
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 115
EP  - 129
VL  - 29
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This research investigated the effects of supervisors' and subordinates' genders on self- and supervisory ratings in an organizational setting. Participants were assemblers, 35 men and 35 women, and their supervisors, 16 men and 19 women. Results showed that subordinates' self-ratings were higher than their supervisors' ratings of them and that gender did not affect the relationship between self- and supervisory ratings. In prior research involving novel situations in laboratory settings, women provided lower self-ratings and higher ratings of others than men. The present study showed no gender differences in ratings on familiar tasks in a real work setting in which performance feedback was available.
AB  - This research investigated the effects of supervisors' and subordinates' genders on self- and supervisory ratings in an organizational setting. Participants were assemblers, 35 men and 35 women, and their supervisors, 16 men and 19 women. Results showed that subordinates' self-ratings were higher than their supervisors' ratings of them and that gender did not affect the relationship between self- and supervisory ratings. In prior research involving novel situations in laboratory settings, women provided lower self-ratings and higher ratings of others than men. The present study showed no gender differences in ratings on familiar tasks in a real work setting in which performance feedback was available.
